//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: one-element tuple
//
// There is nothing at tuple arity one. `()` is unit, `(A)` is a grouping, and
// `(A, B)` is a tuple — but `(A,)` is an error rather than a quietly different
// type from `A`.
//
// The reason is uniformity, not taste. A trailing comma is allowed and
// meaningless in every other list in the grammar: parameters, arguments, record
// fields, generic arguments, list literals, structural types. Making it
// significant in exactly this one place is a rule you would have to remember,
// and `neon fmt` breaks a group across lines by adding a trailing comma — so
// under that rule the formatter could silently turn a grouping into a tuple.
//
// Rust and Python both spend this complexity because macros and trait impls over
// tuple arities need `(T,)`. Neon has neither, so it buys nothing here.

type Single = (str,)

fn main() {}
